        "body": "<p>About two months ago, former <a href=\"https://blavity.com/former-google-engineer-sues-the-company-for-discrimination-against-white-male-conservatives\">Google engineer James Damore</a> made headlines after filing a lawsuit against the huge tech company, for allegedly discriminating against white male conservatives. Now, a similar suit has been <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1quxbLQRFP8H2VGWhhpsjRKxUTXZSXIg7/view\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">filed</a>; this time by a YouTube recruiter, according to <a href=\"https://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2018/03/02/youtube-recruiter-sues-google-hiring-mandates.html\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">Biz Journal</a>.</p><p>Arne Wilberg is suing Google&#39;s sister company, claiming that he was explicitly told not to hire white and Asian men.</p><p>The suit alleges Wilberg&#39;s team was instructed to &ldquo;purge entirely any applications by non-diverse employees from the hiring pipeline,&rdquo; according to the <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/2/17070624/google-youtube-wilberg-recruiter-hiring-reverse-discrimination-lawsuit\">Verge</a>.</p><p>Wilberg claims that his manager sent the team an email that stated, &ldquo;please continue with L3 candidates in process and only accept new L3 candidates that are from historically underrepresented groups.&rdquo;</p><p>Wilberg, who recruited engineers for Google and YouTube&#39;s parent company Alphabet, said he was fired after he made a complaint to upper management about the discriminatory hiring practices; he alleges that other colleagues who complained were either disregarded, transferred or demoted.&nbsp;</p><p>According to Wilberg, executives were also tone-deaf when it came to interacting with recruiters of color. He claims one co-worker&nbsp;&ldquo;complained that managers were speaking about blacks like they were objects,&rdquo; during conversations about an initiative called &quot;Project Mirror,&quot; which was&nbsp; a program where recruiters  interviewed potential hires of their same race or gender.</p><p>To help prove his allegations, Wilberg included a screenshot of a Google tracking system &mdash; which was subsequently deleted &mdash; that kept track of candidates&#39; gender and race, pointing out that the company had not reached their goals in  hiring female, black and Latinx candidates.</p><p>Alphabet has refuted Wilberg&#39;s allegations.</p><p>&ldquo;We have a clear policy to hire candidates based on their merit, not their identity,&rdquo; a Google spokesperson said. &ldquo;At the same time, we unapologetically try to find a diverse pool of qualified candidates for open roles, as this helps us hire the best people, improve our culture, and build better products.&rdquo;</p>",
        "commentStatus": false,
        "excerpt": "A former Google recruiter is suing YouTube for hiring discrimination, claiming that he was explicitly told not to hire white and Asian men.",
